rnwall, England":"Jacobstow, Cornwall, Anglie"},"da":{"1507–1530":"1507–1530","1504–1586":"1504–1586","1527–1557":"1527–1557","1527–1596":"1527–1596","1485–1520":"1485–1520","1557":"1557","1520":"1520","1586":"1586","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","1485":"1485","1507":"1507","1527":"1527","1504":"1504","Poole, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Poole, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Of Poole, Dorset, Eng":"Poole, Dorset, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Jacobstow, Cornwall, England":"Jacobstow, Cornwall, England"},"nl":{"1507–1530":"1507–1530","1504–1586":"1504–1586","1527–1557":"1527–1557","1527–1596":"1527–1596","1485–1520":"1485–1520","1557":"1557","1520":"1520","1586":"1586","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","1485":"1485","1507":"1507","1527":"1527","1504":"1504","Poole, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Poole, Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of Poole, Dorset, Eng":"Poole, Dorset, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Jacobstow, Cornwall, England":"Jacobstow, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1507–1530":"1507–1530","1504–1586":"1504–1586","1527–1557":"1527–1557","1527–1596":"1527–1596","1485–1520":"1485–1520","1557":"1557","1520":"1520","1586":"1586","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","1485":"1485","1507":"1507","1527":"1527","1504":"1504","Poole, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Poole, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Of Poole, Dorset, Eng":"Poole, Dorset, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Jacobstow, Cornwall, England":"Jacobstow, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tovey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire and Somerset): from the Middle English personal name <i>Tovi</i>, <i>Tove</i> (Old Norse <i>Tófi</i>, <i>Tōvi</i>), probably an Old Danish pet form of Old Norse names such as <i>Þorfastr</i>, <i>Þorfinnr</i>, <i>Þorvarðr</i>, and <i>Þorviðr</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jane Tovey was born in 1507, in Cornwall, England as the daughter of Robert Greenville Tovey. She had at least 3 daughters with John Heydon. She died in 1530, in her hometown, at the age of 23."},"et":{"1507–1530":"1507–1530","1504–1586":"1504–1586","1527–1557":"1527–1557","1527–1596":"1527–1596","1485–1520":"1485–1520","1557":"1557","1520":"1520","1586":"1586","1530":"1530","1596":"1596","1485":"1485","1507":"1507","1527":"1527","1504":"1504","Poole, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Poole, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Poole, Dorset, Eng":"Poole, Dorset, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Jacobstow, Cornwall, England":"Jacobstow, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1507–1530":"1507–1530","1504–1586":"1504–1586","1527–1557":"1527–1557","1527–1596":"1527–1596","1485–1520":"1485–1520","1557":"1557","1520":"1520","1586":"1586","